    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the issue is that the system is a very constrained environment, so i can't really run heavy profilers or add a lot of logging overhead without messing with the timing. it's just these very small, incremental leaks that only show up after a long period of time. are there any specific patterns or common coding mistakes in C++ that tend to cause these kinds of \"hidden\" leaks that are hard to spot during standard unit testing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In constrained embedded environments, look closely at raw C-style resource management or usage of containers without proper RAII. A common culprit is forgetting to clear internal state in large data structures or improper handling of smart pointers if they are being manually managed or cast. Another subtle issue is circular references in complex object graphs, especially if you are using raw pointers for parent-child relationships that should be using `std::weak_ptr` (if available).",
      "source": "target",
